<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="188" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,678,1279]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,318,750,775]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body yellow to orange brown. Head yellowish to orange brown, tylus red brown, eyes red. Sulcus of vertex shallow but relatively wide. First antennal segment elongate, slightly thicker apically, basally yellowish brown, apically red, with some dark, stiff, erect setae. Second antennal segment thin, apically slightly club-like, yellowish basally on ¾ of its length, dark reddish apically. Third and fourth antennal segments yellow. Pronotum with apical collar and area of callosities yellow, anterior angles dark reddish, disk slightly punctate and brownish yellow, humeral angles damaged. Legs missing. Scutellum yellowish to orange brown, flat. Clavus and endocorium yellow to orange brown, faintly punctate, exocorium yellowish orange brown tinged with red as cuneus. Membrane light brown, vein red apically. Hemelytral pilosity white, semi-erect, long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="188" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,678,1279]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1038,1063]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Discussion.</emphasis>
The dorsal pilosity and punctation excludes 
<taxonomicName box="[839,958,1038,1063]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Creontiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutus">
<emphasis box="[839,958,1038,1063]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">T. hirsutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1143,1279,1038,1063]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Creontiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1143,1279,1038,1063]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Creontiades</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We were not able to classify the species 
<taxonomicName box="[452,542,1074,1099]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Creontiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutus">
<emphasis box="[452,542,1074,1099]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">hirsutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in any other genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[799,874,1074,1099]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Mirini">Mirini</taxonomicName>
. Consequently, we suggest reinstating 
<taxonomicName authority="Poppius, 1910" authorityName="Poppius" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera" genus="Tricholygus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1304,1435,1074,1099]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Tricholygus</emphasis>
Poppius, 
<number box="[257,313,1111,1135]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" value="1910.0">1910</number>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid genus. The dorsal punctation and the relatively thin antennae could exclude this genus from the 
<emphasis box="[252,701,1146,1171]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">
<taxonomicName box="[252,401,1146,1171]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Adelphocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Adelphocoris</taxonomicName>
- 
<taxonomicName box="[411,547,1146,1171]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Creontiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Creontiades</taxonomicName>
- 
<taxonomicName box="[556,701,1146,1171]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Megacoelum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megacoelum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
complex. Study of additional material (particularly of genitalia of both sexes) would be essential to clarify the placement of this taxon. The species originally described under the binomen 
<taxonomicName authority="Poppius, 1912" authorityName="Poppius" authorityYear="1912" box="[257,652,1218,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera" genus="Tricholygus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis box="[257,483,1218,1243]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Tricholygus grandis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Poppius" box="[491,652,1218,1243]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" refString="Poppius, B. (1912) Die Miriden der Athiopischen Region. Mirina, Cylapina, Bryocorina. Acta Societatis Scientiarum Fennicae, 41 (3), 1 - 203, 1 pl." type="journal article" year="1912">
Poppius, 
<number box="[596,652,1219,1243]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" value="1912.0">1912</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is unknown to us. We tentatively classify it in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1304,1435,1218,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera" genus="Tricholygus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1304,1435,1218,1243]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Tricholygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as presently redefined.
</paragraph>
